.\" termin.al-name: find
.\" termin.al-usage: find [path] [-name pattern]
.\" termin.al-summary: Find virtual paths by a simple wildcard name pattern.
.TH FIND 1 "" "termin.al" "termin.al Manual"
.ftr B R
.ftr I R
.ftr BI R
.SH NAME
find \- Find virtual paths by a simple wildcard name pattern.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
find [path] [-name pattern]
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
Traverses virtual entry names beneath a starting directory and prints matching canonical paths. The default path is the current pane directory and the default pattern is
.BR * .
Paths are resolved only inside the read-only virtual corpus.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B -name pattern
Match each entry's basename with the simple wildcards
.B *
and
.BR ? .
No regular-expression syntax is interpreted. The option may appear before or after the single path operand; a later
.B -name
replaces an earlier pattern.
.SH OUTPUT
The starting directory is included when its own basename matches. Descendants follow deterministic virtual-filesystem traversal order. No match produces no text output.
.SH FAILURES
Unsupported options, a missing pattern, more than one path, invalid or missing paths, files used as the starting path, and locked paths are rejected.
.SH LIMITS
Traversal has a maximum depth of 8 and stops at the application's recursive-entry limit, currently 100 in the browser demo. Truncation keeps the matches already found and adds a
.B runtime.truncated
diagnostic.
.SH NOTES
Cancellation discards the command outcome. Locked descendants may be listed by path because find matches directory entries without reading document contents.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
$ find -name '*.md'
$ find projects -name '*project*'
$ find ~/notes -name 'sample-????.md'
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
tree(1), ls(1), grep(1)
